We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to 

(a) invest on its personnel in the Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction Office by providing them at least the necessary seminar/training as required in the manual; 

(b) prioritize the procurement of disaster related equipment and; 

(c) comply with Rule 6 of RA No. 10121 for Local DRRM office minimum staffing requirement.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant to 

(a) immediately issue the final demand letters to the persons accountable for the outstanding cash advances; 

(b) cause the withholding of their salaries in case of unjustified failure to do so; 

(c) file appropriate administrative or criminal charges, as warranted; and 

(d) strengthen its internal control system on the grant and liquidation of cash advances to avoid the recurrence of similar lapses.

We reiterated our previous year's recommendation and management agreed that the Municipal Accountant 

(a) cause the withholding of salaries of those employees who unjustifiably failed to liquidate their long outstanding cash advances despite demand; 

(b) refrain from granting additional cash advances to accountable officers and employees with unliquidated cash advances; 

(c) file appropriate legal action, if warranted, against those who have failed to liquidate the overdue cash advances after exhausting appropriate means, including those who are no longer in the government service; and 

(d) request for write-off of unliquidated cash advances of deceased person

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct the:

(a) 		Municipal Engineer to (i) submit the approved suspension orders for the two projects; otherwise explain why the contractor was allowed time extensions without approved Suspension Orders; (ii) conduct timely monitoring and evaluation of the work accomplishment in accordance with the project schedule; and (iii) comply with publicity requirement of government projects by installing accurate and appropriate billboards at the start and end of the project; 

(b) 	BAC to  submit, through the Municipal Accountant, the lacking documents and ensure that the submitted supporting documents are original copies and complete in accordance with the aforesaid laws, agreement and rules and regulations.

5.11	We commended the LGU officials actions to comply with R.A. No. 9003 and further recommended that Management;
(a) comply with all the requirements set by the DENR to obtain the Environmental Compliance Certificate needed so that the sanitary landfill may be utilized;
(b) instruct the designated MENRO to review the existing 10-year SWM Plan and recommend updates necessary for the complete approval of its 10-year plan;
(c) instruct the designated MENRO to recommend updates, amendments and ratification of any existing municipal ordinance related to managing solid wastes to the Sangguniang Bayan (SB), or any policies and possible measures that is in accordance with the provisions of RA No. 9003
(d) strengthen the implementation of ordinance imposing fines and penalties for violators of the Anti-Littering policy as well as filing of administrative cases against erring government officials as provided by Sections 49 and 50 of RA No. 9003.
(e) strictly observed the implementation of RA No. 9003;

12.6	We recommended the Local Chief Executive to:
(a) encourage and direct the GFPS Committee and Technical Working Group to perform their mandated tasks and;
(b) establish and maintain a GAD Database to ensure responsiveness of GAD Plan and Budget to gender issues, woman empowerment, and to sustain the LGUs critical consciousness in supporting gender and development.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive instruct the  

(a) Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to conduct reconciliation of their respective Cash-in-Bank records at least on a quarterly basis;  

(b) Municipal Accountant to  

(i) secure print-out or snap shot copies of the Banks Statements as an alternative basis in preparing BRS; 

(ii) immediately prepare bank reconciliation statements for the early detection of errors that may require adjustment either in the bank records or in the books of the Municipality; and 

(iii) observe the prescribed period in the submission of Bank Reconciliation Statements to the Office of the Auditor.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive: 

require the Municipal Accountant to (i) send demand letters to the concerned accountable officers for the liquidation of their accountabilities; (ii) stop the practice of granting new cash advances without the liquidation of previous ones; and (iii) require the concerned personnel to liquidate their cash advances as soon as the purpose thereof had been accomplished; 

require the Cashiers/Disbursing Officers to ensure that their reports of disbursements are complete with the needed documentation and information; 

require the Accounting personnel in-charge of Subsidiary Ledgers to regularly update and monitor the same for accurate  monitoring of granting and liquidation of cash advances; 

require the Disbursing Officers and the Accounting Staff in the Accounting Office to conduct regular reconciliation of their records with the Treasury Records; 

require the Municipal Accountant to review, analyze and reconcile all dormant cash advance accounts and derecognize all dormant accounts pursuant to the Guidelines on the Proper Disposition/Closure of Dormant Funds and/or Accounts as provided in COA Circular No. 97-001 dated February 5, 1997; and 

direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to withhold salaries of accountable officers who fail to submit the liquidation reports of their outstanding cash advances.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive 

 instruct the GAD Focal Person and Municipal Budget Officer to prepare its GAD Plan and allocate the budget pursuant to DBM/NEDA/NCRFW Joint Circular No. 01;

and comply with the essential elements of GAD Planning and Budgeting to be able to identify, prioritize and address gender issues and gaps.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Treasurer  conduct annual physical count of PPE and submit a report thereon, copy furnished the Accounting Department for information and reference;

Accountant (i) comply with the provision of PPSAS No. 17 on the provision of depreciation on PPE accounts; and (ii) account for the prior  years’ PPE ledger balance by updating the SLs and completing PPELC using the old accounting files as references.

We recommended that Members of the Provincial Local School Board:

prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization and stop the practice of accommodating expenditures for activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;

request for inputs from the Deped official/ School Division Superintendent in the prioritization of SEF projects and expenditures in accordance with the DepEd criteria and with due regard to the provisions of R.A. No. 5447, Sections 100 and 272, RA 7160 and Deped-DBM-DILG Joint Circular prescribing the limitations on the use of the fund;

maximize the utilization of SEF to attain its objectives, monitor the implementation of the Project Program Activities (PPA’s), and take appropriate actions such as realignment or reprograming, if necessary.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
require the Municipal Accountant to (i) send demand letters to the concerned accountable officers for the liquidation of their accountabilities; (ii) stop the practice of granting new cash advances without the liquidation of previous ones; and (iii) require the concerned personnel to liquidate their cash advances as soon as the purpose thereof had been accomplished;
require the Cashiers/Disbursing Officers to ensure that their reports of disbursements are complete with the needed documentation and information;
require the Accounting personnel in-charge of Subsidiary Ledgers to regularly update and monitor the same for accurate  monitoring of granting and liquidation of cash advances;
require the Disbursing Officers and the Accounting Staff in the Accounting Office to conduct regular reconciliation of their records with the Treasury Records;
require the Municipal Accountant to review, analyze and reconcile all dormant cash advance accounts and derecognize all dormant accounts pursuant to the Guidelines on the Proper Disposition/Closure of Dormant Funds and/or Accounts as provided in COA Circular No. 97-001 dated February 5, 1997; and
direct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to withhold salaries of accountable officers who fail to submit the liquidation reports of their outstanding cash advances.
2.9	The management commented that it has not yet issued clearances to those who are already resigned with unliquidated cash advances sent. Demand letters were sent to all accountable officers stating therein that failure to liquidate after the lapse of the designated time, deduction/refund shall be started as a way of collection.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor (a) instruct the BUB Focal Person of the respective implementing offices to strictly monitor the  implementation of projects and take note of any gaps/issues for future references or subsequent administrative action; and (b) instruct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) and Municipal Accountant  to strictly adhere to the provisions of R.A. No. 9184 for projects involving procurement and submit the lacking documents required under COA Circular No. 2012-001, to avoid suspension and/or disallowance in audit.
In the exit conference, the management that the following factors contributed to the non-implementation of some projects and programs, to wit:
Bidding conducted failed due to absence of interested bidders;
Suppliers in the locality are not registered in the PhilGeps as required under RA 9184;
The municipality were not furnished by the source agency of the approved Memorandum of Agreement; and
There were insertions/amendments in the proposed programs/projects made by the source national agencies without consulting the LGU concerned, hence difficulty in the implementation of said projects.
